# SaaS Ops Copilot

An AI-powered GitHub repository intelligence dashboard. Connect your GitHub account and get instant visibility into dormant repos, security risks, cost waste, and AI-generated action plans — in under 30 seconds.

![Dashboard Preview](https://placehold.co/1200x600/0a0f1e/6366f1?text=SaaS+Ops+Copilot+Dashboard)
> _Replace the above with a real screenshot before publishing_

---

## What it does

Most engineering teams have repos they've forgotten about — old experiments, temp migration scripts, abandoned services sitting public on GitHub. Each one is a potential security leak and a CI/CD cost drain.

SaaS Ops Copilot scans your GitHub account or org and gives you:

- **Risk Scores (0–100)** — every repo scored on inactivity, public exposure, and security posture
- **Security Findings** — detects name-pattern risks (`secret-`, `backup-`, `temp-`), public repos inactive 180+ days, likely CVE exposure
- **Cost Waste Estimation** — calculates monthly CI/CD spend on dormant repos in dollars
- **AI Recommendations** — per-repo action plans: archive, review, reassign — with business impact and suggested commands
- **Repo Health Table** — full overview of active vs dormant vs critical repos
- **AI Copilot Chat** — ask questions in natural language: _"which repo is most at risk?"_, _"how much am I wasting?"_, _"top 3 actions?"_
- **Action Buttons** — one-click flows to create Jira tickets, send Slack alerts, email team leads, or archive repos _(UI demonstrated with mock responses; see [Roadmap](#roadmap) for real integrations)_

---

## Tech Stack

**Frontend**
- React 19 + TypeScript
- Vite 8
- React Router v7
- Recharts (data visualisation)
- Pure CSS-in-JS (no UI library dependency)

**Backend**
- Python 3.12
- FastAPI
- SQLAlchemy + PostgreSQL
- Authlib (GitHub OAuth 2.0)
- Starlette Sessions

**Auth & Security**
- GitHub OAuth — token never touches a URL or localStorage
- Short-lived one-time code exchange → httpOnly cookie session
- All API endpoints read auth from the cookie via FastAPI `Depends`

---

## Architecture

```
Browser
  │
  ├─ GET  /auth/github/login          → redirects to GitHub OAuth
  ├─ GET  /auth/github/callback       → issues one-time code, redirects to /callback
  ├─ POST /auth/github/exchange       → validates code, sets httpOnly cookie
  │
  ├─ POST /auth/github/sync           → fetches repos + commits from GitHub API → PostgreSQL
  │
  ├─ GET  /analytics/repository-summary
  ├─ GET  /analytics/risk-scores
  ├─ GET  /analytics/cost-waste
  ├─ GET  /analytics/dormant-repositories
  ├─ GET  /security/findings
  └─ GET  /ai/recommendations
```

---

## Local Setup

### Prerequisites

- Node.js 18+
- Python 3.12+
- PostgreSQL running locally
- A GitHub OAuth App ([create one here](https://github.com/settings/applications/new))

### 1. Clone the repo

```bash
git clone https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/ai-saas-copilot.git
cd ai-saas-copilot
```

### 2. Backend

```bash
cd backend
python -m venv venv
source venv/bin/activate        # Windows: venv\Scripts\activate
pip install -r requirements.txt
```

Create `backend/.env`:

```env
GITHUB_CLIENT_ID=your_github_client_id
GITHUB_CLIENT_SECRET=your_github_client_secret
DATABASE_URL=postgresql://postgres:yourpassword@localhost/saascopilot
FRONTEND_URL=http://localhost:5173
SESSION_SECRET=any-long-random-string
```

Set your GitHub OAuth App's callback URL to:
```
http://localhost:8000/auth/github/callback
```

Create the database and run:

```bash
# Create the DB (first time only)
psql -U postgres -c "CREATE DATABASE saascopilot;"

# Start the backend
uvicorn main:app --reload --port 8000
```

### 3. Frontend

```bash
cd frontend
npm install
```

Create `frontend/.env`:

```env
VITE_API_URL=http://localhost:8000
```

```bash
npm run dev
```

Open [http://localhost:5173](http://localhost:5173)

---

## How the OAuth flow works

Most apps pass the GitHub token in the redirect URL (`/?token=abc`) — this leaks it into browser history, server logs, and analytics tools.

This app uses a safer pattern:

1. GitHub redirects to the backend callback
2. Backend generates a **one-time code** (32-byte random, in-memory, single use)
3. Browser is redirected to `/callback?code=<one-time-code>` — not the real token
4. Frontend immediately POSTs the code to `/auth/github/exchange`
5. Backend validates, **deletes** the code (replay returns 400), sets an **httpOnly cookie**
6. All subsequent API calls send the cookie automatically — the token is never accessible to JavaScript

